&lt;h4 id="self-healing" class="heading-link">
 &lt;strong>self-healing&lt;/strong>
 &lt;a href="#self-healing" class="heading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink to this heading">ðŸ”—&lt;/a>
&lt;/h4>
&lt;p>Kubernetes restarts containers that fail, replaces containers, kills containers that don&amp;rsquo;t respond to your user-defined health check, and doesn&amp;rsquo;t advertise them to clients until they are ready to serve.&lt;/p>

&lt;h4 id="automatic-bin-packing" class="heading-link">
 &lt;strong>automatic bin packing&lt;/strong>
 &lt;a href="#automatic-bin-packing" class="heading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink to this heading">ðŸ”—&lt;/a>
&lt;/h4>
&lt;p>You provide Kubernetes with a cluster of nodes that it can use to run containerized tasks. You tell Kubernetes how much CPU and RAM each container needs. Kubernetes can fit containers onto your nodes to make the best use of your resources.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Positoning</title><link>https://cloud.layer5.io/academy/learning-paths/98e16360-a366-4b78-8e0a-031da07fdacb/sks-starter/kubernetes/content/positioning/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://cloud.layer5.io/academy/learning-paths/98e16360-a366-4b78-8e0a-031da07fdacb/sks-starter/kubernetes/content/positioning/</guid><description>&lt;h3 id="positoning" class="heading-link">
